		<paragraph x="12" y="+4" width="605" height="0" style="headline" tabs="0" indent="0"><![CDATA[<B><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="12" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Look carefully at the flow chart and complete the report by choosing the word or phrase which best fits each gap.</B></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT></B>]]></paragraph>
	</title>
	<body>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+16" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">The flow chart shows how theatre companies advertise themselves and their productions.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;</P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">The company might want to advertise even if tickets for a specific event are not yet available. This can be done through what is known as a 'teaser' campaign, which stimulates public interest before subsequent campaigns reveal exactly what the event is. [1], an 'awareness' campaign can be used to inform the public about the work of the company in general. [2], on the other hand, tickets are available, [3] organisers will need to run a campaign designed specifically to increase sales.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;</P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Whatever the campaign, there are three basic steps that need to be followed. [4], the schedule must be planned. [5], the actual advertisements need to be designed. [6], the campaign starts running.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;</P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">[7] the advertisements are part of a sales campaign, the company needs to know how effective they are. [8] the campaign is running, ticket sales are monitored. [9] sales figures are disappointing, then the company can [10] redesign the advertisements [11] drop the campaign altogether. [12], if sales figures are good, it is probably worth continuing the campaign.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph height="0" width="605" y="+16" x="12"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="2"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
