	<feedback mode="101" id="1">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Alternatively</B><FONT COLOR="#000000">: This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Subsequently:</B> The diagram shows that the company can either run a teaser campaign or an awareness campaign. The awareness campaign doesn't follow the teaser campaign.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Prior to this:</B> 'Prior to' means 'before'. The diagram doesn't show that first an awareness campaign is run and then a teaser campaign.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="2">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>If:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Unless:</B> 'Unless' means 'if not'.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Whether:</B> 'Whether' can sometimes be used to mean 'if', for example in reported speech, with prepositions or after certain verbs. However, it's not appropriate here.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="3">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>then:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>otherwise:</B> This can't be used because the sentence begins with 'if'.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>when:</B> The missing word here shows that something happens only if a certain condition is true.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="4">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>First of all:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Firstly:</B> This is used to introduce a list of reasons or arguments in a discursive composition.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Once:</B> 'Once' is used to mean 'when something is completed or finished'.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="5">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Next:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Finally:</B> If you look at the flow chart, you'll see that this isn't the final step of the three.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Initially:</B> This means 'at first'.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="6">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Finally:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>At the end:</B> This expression isn't used to list items or stages in a process.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>In the end:</B> This expression is used in stories, not in reports like this one.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="7">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>If:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Provided:</B> 'Provided' has a similar meaning to 'if', but they are not used in exactly the same way. 'Provided' means that something will happen 'only if' a certain condition is true.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>While:</B> This is used to show that two things are happening at the same time. This sentence refers to the alternatives which the company face when they are deciding what kind of campaign to run. Go back to the top of the flow chart.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="8">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>While:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>After:</B> If you look at the flow chart you'll see that the monitoring of ticket sales takes place all through the sales advertising campaign. Two stages in the process are taking place at the same time.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>If:</B> 'Ticket monitoring' is not an alternative stage in the process. If you look at the flow chart you'll see that it takes place all through the sales advertising campaign. Two stages in the process are taking place at the same time.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="9">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>If:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>In case:</B> 'In case' is similar in meaning to if, but it is not appropriate here. 'In case' is used when we refer to precautions that are taken. 'Take an umbrella with you, in case it rains', for example.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Whether:</B> 'Whether' can sometimes be used to mean 'if', for example in reported speech, with prepositions or after certain verbs. However, it's not appropriate here.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="10">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>either:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>or:</B> As you've noticed, this sentence describes the alternative stages shown at the bottom of the flow chart. However, you've used the wrong connector.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>neither:</B> 'Neither' means not one and not the other.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="11">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>or:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>neither:</B> 'Neither' means not one and not the other.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>nor:</B> This means 'not the other'.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
	</feedback>
	<feedback mode="101" id="12">
		<paragraph x="0" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#0000FF" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>On the other hand:</B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> This is the correct answer.</FONT></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Finally:</B> If you look at the flow chart you'll see that this is not the end of the process, although it is the end of the report.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT><TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0"><B>Then:</B> This sentence refers to the diamond which says, 'Are tickets selling well?' This is an 'alternative' stage.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
